==English==

===Etymology===
{{F.}} ''[[dénoncer]]'', {{OF.}} ''[[denoncier]]'', from {{L.}} ''[[denuntiare]]'', ''[[denunciare]]''; from ''[[de-]]'' + ''[[nunciare]]'', ''[[nuntiare]]'' "to announce, report", from ''[[nuntius]]'' "messenger, message."

===Verb===
{{en-infl-reg-other-e|denounc|e}}

# {{transitive}} {{archaic}} To make known in a [[formal]] manner; to [[proclaim]]; to [[announce]]; to [[declare]].
#: ''denouncing wrath to come'' (Milton)
# {{transitive}} To [[criticize]] or [[speak out]] against (someone or something); to point out as deserving of [[reprehension]] or [[punishment]], etc.; to openly [[accuse]] or [[condemn]] in a threatening manner; to invoke [[censure]] upon; to [[stigmatize]].
#: ''to denounce someone as a swindler, or as a coward''
# {{transitive}} To make formal or [[public]] [[accusation]] against; to [[inform]] against; to [[accuse]].
#: ''to denounce a confederate in crime''
#: ''to denounce someone to the authorities''
# {{transitive}} To [[proclaim]] in a [[threaten]]ing manner; to threaten by some [[outward]] [[sign]] or [[expression]]; make a [[menace]] of.
#: ''to denounce war; to denounce punishment''
# {{transitive}} To [[announce]] the [[termination]] of; especially a [[treaty]] or [[armistice]].

====Synonyms====
* (''criticize or speak out against'') [[criticize]], [[speak out]]
* (''openly accuse'') [[accuse]], [[blame]]
* (''formally accuse'') [[accuse]], [[charge]], [[report]]
* (''give away information about'') [[give away]], [[snitch]], [[tell]]
* (''announce the termination of; especially a treaty'') [[withdraw from]]

